{{Infobox person | image = File:Terence Smith.png | caption = Terence Smith on [[PBS NewsHour]] in 2017 | birth_date = 1938 | birth_name = Terence F. Smith | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. | occupation = Journalist | years_active = 1965–present | spouse = Susanne Stout | partner = | children = two | parents = [[Red Smith (sportswriter)|Walter Wellesley (Red) Smith]], sportswriter | relatives = }}
'''Terence Smith''' is an [[United States|American]] journalist who worked as a special correspondent at [[The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer]], worked for ''[[The New York Times]]'', and [[CBS News]]. Smith has been a guest host for [[The Diane Rehm Show]], and contributes to [[The Huffington Post]]. At CBS, Smith won two [[Emmy Award]]s, in 1990 for his coverage of [[Hurricane Hugo]], and in 1989 for his coverage of people who live near nuclear power plants. He retired from [[PBS NewsHour]] in 2006.<ref>[http://terencefsmith.com/?p=32 About Terence Smith]</ref> He has strong environmental interests and served on the Advisory Board of the [[Smithsonian Environmental Research Center]]<ref>[https://www.si.edu/content/governance/pdf/actions_9-07.pdf Minutes of the Board of Regents, September 17, 2007. APPENDIX A, APPROVED RESOLUTIONS], [[Smithsonian Institution]]</ref> and Chairs the Board of the Maryland Chesapeake Bay Trust of the State of [[Maryland]].<ref>[http://msa.maryland.gov/msa/mdmanual/25ind/html/18ches.html Organizational structure of the Maryland Chesapeake Bay Trust]</ref>
Smith was born to sportswriter [[Red Smith (sportswriter)|Red Smith]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE5D6143FF930A15750C0A96E948260|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120716075726/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE5D6143FF930A15750C0A96E948260|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2012-07-16|title=SPORTS PEOPLE; Red Smith Honor|publisher=New York Times|date=1988-03-23}}</ref> and later earned a [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor of Arts degree]] from the [[University of Notre Dame]] in 1960.<ref>[http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/University_Notre_Dame_Dome_Yearbook/1960/Page_345.html 1960 Notre Dame Dome Yearbook, page 345]</ref>
Smith is married and has two grown children and three grandchildren. He lives in the Eastport neighborhood in [[Annapolis, Maryland]], on the shore of the Chesapeake Bay.<ref>[http://terencefsmith.com/?page_id=8 Terence Smith website] retrieved August 12, 2012</ref>
